column168: XPO Logistics terminal NML experienced a UN3109 TBHP-70-AQ release from a 5-gallon jerrican due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and advised terminal personnel had already conducted cleanup and placed the damaged jug and impacted absorbents into a closed top poly drum. The crew removed the damaged jug from the drum and placed it into a 55-gallon vented poly drum, confirming 1-gallon released. The impacted drum was then cut up and containerized along with the impacted absorbents into a separate 55-gallon vented poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XTM experienced an over the road release of UN1760 Biocide 4 from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 23' x 5' area of the trailer floor and a 50’ x 2’ area of the gravel lot below due to a puncture caused by a broken pallet. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Floor dry and a citric acid solution were then deployed and utilized to clean the impacted areas. The impacted gravel was shoveled up and the area pH came back at a 7 once all contaminants were removed. All impacted gravel and absorbents were containerized into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Tomah, WI and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XSG experienced a UN3103 TBPB release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors for containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released to the box only due to the vented cap releasing as a result of load shift. The jugs were removed from the impacted box and wiped down for shipment on. The impacted cardboard was neutralized with water and containerized along with the impacted rags and PPE into a vented 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

All impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. column168: On October 9, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3098 was punctured and released approximately 467-gallons of product to the trailer interior, lift gate, and asphalt roadway. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to remediate the impacted site. AS personnel utilized a vacuum pump to transfer the undamaged product from the damaged tote to a new tote and secured for normal transport. Crews then deployed additional granular absorbent and a neutralizing agent to the impacted trailer floor, lift gate and asphalt roadway and worked them in utilizing hand tools. All UN3098 impacted material, including the damaged tote, was collected and containerized in nine (9) 55-gallon drums and were taken to  RLC-SJE to be staged and added to the facility waste stream. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date for pressure washing of impacted asphalt and monitor waste at RLC-SJE.  On Oct 11, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. The waste was still reacting and drums were left unsealed in an open trailer. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date to continue monitoring the waste at RLC-SJE.  On Oct 12, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. There was olfactory evidence that the waste was still reacting and drums were left unsealed in an open trailer. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date to continue monitoring the waste at RLC-SJE.  On Oct 13, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. The reaction had ceased. The impacted trailer was re-inspected and it was confirmed that no further remediation necessary at the direction of RLC personnel. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date to secure the waste at RLC-SJE to be added to the facility waste stream.  On Oct 16, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. The reaction had ceased and drums were secured. RLC personnel took possession of nine (9) 55-gallon drums of waste to be added to the facility waste stream.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: On October 16, 2023, Aerolinahs Brasileiras S.A.’s (DBA LATAM Cargo Brasil, formerly TAM Cargo) flight 8473 departed from Miami International Airport. Approximately 30 minutes after takeoff, the flight returned to Miami International Airport due to the detection of a strong chemical smell from the Main Deck.     2. Cargo Area Inspection:     Upon the flight's return to Miami International Airport, the Miami Dade Fire Department was called to investigate the situation. They requested that the Main Deck be opened to ventilate the area and check for any potential leakage of dangerous goods.     3. Identification of the Chemical:     During the inspection, a pallet in position 2R was identified to contain RFL UN1089 Acetaldehyde. This pallet was promptly removed from its position for further examination. It was later determined that there was no spill of the substance either on the pallet or on the floor of the aircraft.     4. Safety Measures and Gas Dissipation:     Following the removal of the pallet, the Miami Dade Fire Department allowed the aircraft to remain open for approximately 30 minutes to ensure proper ventilation and to monitor the situation. After this time, the Fire Department’s team conducted a cargo inspection and, having found no further issues, cleared the plane for operation. The pallet involved in the incident was isolated for an additional 40 minutes to allow any lingering gases to dissipate, making it safe for handling.     5. Preliminary Investigation Findings:     During the preliminary investigation, it was confirmed that all procedures for handling dangerous goods were followed correctly. While there may have been a partial smell of non-toxic gas, it was determined that the packaging containing the Acetaldehyde was not damaged, and therefore, it did not pose a safety risk.

column168: On October 19, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of printing ink was impacted by a skid and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from E3/OMI (E3) to remediate the impacted site. . E3 personnel deployed granular absorbents to the printing ink-impacted floor and swept them in with hand tools. They cut up the impacted pallet and all spent absorbents and waste were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and one (1) 85-gallon over pack for transport and disposal.

column168: On October 19, 2023, ten (10) 5-gallon bladders of UN3267 were punctured by a forklift and released approximately seven (7) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the impacted site.  EWI personnel neutralized and collected the released product with citric acid, and they repeated this process until no corrosive liquid remained and the surface had a neutral pH. Crews cut-up the impacted pallet with hand tools. All neutralized product, the cut-up pallet, the ten (10) damaged bladders, and cleanup debris were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon poly drums that were staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column168: On October 25, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN1866 were crushed in transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer floor, tires, and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel collected two (2) damaged 5-gallon pails of UN1866 for disposal. Crews then deployed granular absorbent to the impacted trailer floor and pavement beneath trailer and worked them in utilizing hand tools. Once collected, TLE personnel utilized a degreasing agent with absorbent pads to collect any residual product on trailer floor, trailer tires and pavement. All undamaged freight was re-stacked and secured for normal transport. All UN1866 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 85-gallon drum and two (2) 35-gallon drums and RLC personnel took possession of the waste.
